##FOREIGNERS REFUSING TO LEAVE WUHAN: 30 magical days

MICRO-SIGNAL YITIAOTV

Feature description, a short original video every day, every day to tell a moving story, every day selected human beauty, every day to live a better life with me.

After the city closure in Wuhan, the United States, Japan, Australia and other countries,

They're sending planes to evacuate the Chinese.

Who Goes and who stays?

The international family that Haunts Wuhan.

Many families choose to let one party leave with their children,

There are plenty of options for the whole family to stay.

A French doctor who lives in Wuhan said,

"during the outbreak, I was able to do more in Wuhan than in France. "

Another Japanese professor's response was widely circulated on the Internet:

"I have Chinese students in my lab,

I can not escape to Japan without my colleagues and students."

Those who leave or those who stay,

In a fragile and tender place.

Speak for yourself, Fred

Editor Ye Lixiao Yue

Fred's shop is located on Lihuangpi road and is well known in Wuhan

On January 23, the day the city was shut down in Wuhan, Xiao Yu, who was returning to his parents'home for the Spring Festival, asked his wife, Anna, who is British and German, to contact the embassy for information.

Meanwhile, Fred, a Frenchman who has lived in Wuhan for 10 years on Li Huangpi Road, closed his three small shops ahead of time, and call the Chinese parents-in-law to explain: "This year's dinner can not eat together, you old people also do not go out. "

An Australian Chinese visiting his family in Wuhan, China, on his way to Wuhan Tianhe Airport

In Hubei, 18,000 permanent residents of foreign nationality live in the city, with 80 percent concentrated in Wuhan.

They say behind every number, there's a person; behind every person, there's a family.

Flights between Wuhan and the rest of the world were grounded after the city was closed on January 23. Foreigners in the storm face the same daily challenges as locals: The loss of public transport makes it difficult to buy supplies; children and the elderly need more care; people with their own illnesses can not go to the hospital; Some people had planned to go back to work after the Spring Festival holiday. They may also have another problem: their Chinese is not good enough to get and understand information about the outbreak in the first place.

So many people began to turn to the embassy for help.

According to various media reports, as of February 22, the number of expats evacuated from various countries

In the face of evacuation, leaving and staying are both choices that are not only personal. Once a family is involved, the issues become more complicated.

Xiao Yu and his multinational family, in a hurry and under pressure, chose to let his wife leave with their children, while Fred and his wife, after much deliberation, decided to stay together as a family.

We had an in-depth conversation with these two families who made different choices. Their experiences also reflect the plight of the entire community of foreigners and international families in Wuhan, as well as in Hubei, in dealing with the epidemic.

Had just escaped the Australian fire,

Another outbreak in Wuhan

My Wife, Anna, and I have lived in Oxford since 2014. I was doing a phd in political science at Oxford, where Anna was studying East Asian traditional music, and she was a dual national of England and Germany. Six months ago, we moved to Australia from England.

Back to Wuhan is the Spring Festival home, but earlier than planned, we returned early in January, to escape the Australian fire.

When traffic in Wuhan stopped on Jan. 23, I urged Anna to contact the embassy and ask her to take the children out. At first, she didn't call it an emergency. She just logged in. She was unfazed, more submissive than we were, and said it didn't matter, "I've seen it as normal" since the December escape.

January 25(the first day of the New Year) rainy night, the third day of the city of Wuhan, a car out to refuel, to the second day of the New Year out of the fuel limit

Anna's anxiety began on the second day of the Lunar New Year (January 26) , when a two-year-old child in Guangxi province was diagnosed. Our child is not yet three years old. Before this, we said that will not infect the child, to each other in the mind comfort, who dare not be sure. The virus has finally broken the age barrier.

And the child's vocabulary is growing, in Australia to learn "fire" , in Wuhan to learn "cough" and "mask.

On January 26th the Nikkei News reported that two countries, Japan and the US, were preparing to repatriate their citizens from Wuhan; on January 31st the BBC reported the arrival of a British evacuation flight

Who Goes, who stays,

A never-ending discussion begins at home

On January 27th Britain launched its evacuation programme, and Anna called to enter his identity and contact information. She said, "I put your message in. They said the family can go together. ". I said, Anna, if you can go, I'll stay. My parents, my grandmother, they're still here. Young people have the best chance of surviving the virus, so I'm GonNa stay here until the lockdown is over. I understand, Anna said.

A never-ending discussion begins at home.

Father said: "One can go is one, you stay, can do? " I said: "I will take a long vacation. " Mother asked: "You stay in the end what purpose. " Father replied: "He does not want to be called a deserter. "

On January 28th, a German request to send a military aircraft was denied. Two days in a row, Anna said, the French did it. She can not for the life of her life believe that her two countries are lagging behind their neighbours. She spends her days in her room, making phone calls and e-mailing, not missing a single piece of gossip. Her parents, far away in Europe, already live in China's time zone.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On Jan. 31, several media outlets quoted German Foreign Minister Heiko Maias as as saying that Germany would send a chartered plane to evacuate the Chinese from Wuhan

Finally, as the family watched don't tell her, Anna, seated in a chair, stood up and we waited for her announcement.

"The Germans are coming, " she said, "but we're being quarantined for two weeks. " The trouble doesn't stop there. Those who leave have to go through a medical examination and can not leave if they have symptoms. It doesn't say if the kids and their families can go with them.

Children and their families are at the centre of a two-day stand-off at the airport on January 29th by a British evacuation plane.

At home, the mother changed the adult mask into a child's mask, folding it inwards and sewing it on. Father, get the authorities to drive to the airport. Reluctantly, Anna signed off on the mandatory quarantine. I'm making a children's movie for the quarantine. The kids were surprised to find that we were packing a lot of daily allowance cookies and movies for the trip. I said, it's Chinese New Year, and it's not over yet.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the night of January 31, Xiao Yu's family went to the airport

No one knows how long to wait at the airport before leaving,

We didn't say much good-bye

On the last night of January, we set off. The German plane arrived a day early, and we were asked to be at the airport by eight o'clock.

When the traffic lights when the motorcycle drag, a left and a right, in the open road gallop. The inspectors with the lists checked at the airport tollgates before going through the military. The blast-proof test at the airport gate became a temperature test. There were Koreans, Indians, Bengali people, Sri Lankans, Turks, Germans in the departure hall.

Three German officers showed up wearing orange vests. They somehow got a Chinese wooden table and two chairs. From the bag, take out the German flag on the corner of the table, began to register.

Thanks to the tug-of-war in front of the British, children and their families can all get on the plane today. A stone has been lifted from our hearts, but no one knows for how long.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the night of January 31st, inside the Wuhan Tianhe International Airport

From eight o'clock to eleven o'clock, the child ran tired in the airport, also do not want to wear a mask. I put him to bed in the car, away from the airport crowd. He made me carry him in the front seat. After midnight, my arm went numb and I fell asleep until my phone rang.

3:30 in the morning, no progress. It's chilly at the airport. At first, the heavily guarded crowd was overwhelmed. They took off their masks and gloves and ate snacks and instant noodles freely. After another two hours of this, we checked in our bags and started lining up for a physical.

The child in Anna's arms, dressed in a red coat, looked like a fire, opened his eyes and said, "go home, grandma and GRANDPA. " None of us spoke.

I said, "I'm not going with you and mom this time. If mom doesn't let you see Petch, you call me, " he said, and we left together. We were in such a hurry that we didn't have time to inoculate him for separation.

We didn't have much to say good-bye, two days of little rest, thirsty, dizzy. They disappeared into white and yellow suits. The plane didn't leave until 9:00 the next morning.

Outside the exclusion zone of the German military barracks of Gammsheim

POST-DEPARTURE SEGREGATION:

Every member of the family is stressed out, and the children are especially stressed out

Now, we maintain daily video chats, including with Mrs.'s parents, who are more anxious than we are.

Germany's quarantine policy is to check every day, and if a new infection is found among the more than 100 quarantined passengers, the quarantine period has to be recalculated, that is, restarted for two weeks. It's causing a lot of psychological stress for everyone. (there were two confirmed cases on the evacuation flight.)

The camp is a single-room isolation, similar to a hotel room, with public activity space, can be down in the courtyard activities. The quarantine zone is run by volunteers from the German Red Cross, and friends and relatives are not allowed to send packages inside.

The initial conditions can not meet the needs of the family, such as children with food and cutlery shortage, eating is also relatively simple, after making adjustments. The next day, the volunteers brought the children's toys and gradually enriched their diet. Among the quarantines are yoga instructors who organize yoga classes. Everyone's a lot more relaxed right now.

But for the child, he still does not understand why can not go out, it is a test and suffering for him. On Feb. 17, the day after the 14 day quarantine ended, they tested again, confirming that none of the people in the group had responded and had returned home.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan after the siege by Wang Lang

"dogmatic tenderness, "

Is My understanding of family in this crisis

In Wuhan, I live with my parents and my grandmother. Right now, our neighborhood is completely sealed off.

My mother said, we live in it, but not so nervous. Death is closer to us. People we know are diagnosed and suspicious, but no one talks about death as if it were immediately upon them. When we get nervous, all we can think about is who's infected at home, who's infected at home, and what to do about it. Even if the infection, think of is: Bad, relatives and friends to do, those who contact it.

Wuhan people have no special information channels. Like netizens across the country, we get first-hand information from the media and the Internet, and rely on wechat groups of relatives and friends to spread it.

We read individual stories like everyone else, but we never talk about them in front of our families. Not to deny those desperate experiences, but to be close to them.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In March 2019, while on an expedition to Colombia,

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In May 2019, during an expedition to Syria,

For Research Purposes, I often travel to conflict or humanitarian crisis areas. In 2019, he traveled to Venezuela and Syria to witness the separation of families. Objectively speaking, our separation is just a small wave, there is no life and death. One might even say that the option of evacuation is a luxury.

But it still has a big impact on families. The question we've been wrestling with is: Do we get out as often as we can, or do we make it a priority to keep our families together? The meaning of preservation, in the end is the family to overcome difficulties, or the continuation of life? WORST-CASE SCENARIO, family goes down together, family goes down. But what's the point of being alone if one of US survives?

Our final agreement was: let the children go when they can.

Of course, the only thing this decision was without consulting the child. Even though he's older and understands the situation, if he doesn't want to leave, will we take his advice? I'm afraid not.

Family decisions can be tender, but they can also be arbitrary. Arbitrary Warmth, that's what I understand about family through this crisis.

Fred's family of three and his in-laws

Separate from each other at home in Wuhan

My wife Vicky and I met in Wuhan in 2015. She is from Wuhan and her parents and relatives are in Wuhan. We just had our baby born last year.

Closing up early, giving out masks

I have lived in Wuhan for 10 years, and my wife and I run three shops, a coffee shop, a clothing store and a design studio on one of the most beautiful streets in Wuhan -- Foshan Huangpo road.

I knew the news of the new type of pneumonia came on December 31 last year, when pictures of the South China Seafood Market began circulating on the Internet, and when I heard the explanation was "unknown cause, " I knew something was wrong.

In recent years, viral infections such as Zaire ebolavirus and the H1N1 flu outbreak have been so frequent that I immediately handed out masks to every one of my staff. Several of the employees joked with me, "Fred, it's crazy to wear a mask right now. "

On January 20th, on second thought, I decided to close all the stores ahead of schedule. Three stores have a lot of traffic every day, in case of staff infection, the consequences are very serious, I dare not take this risk.

Vicky and darling

I advised my wife to take my son and stay:

Even as a foreigner to encourage people to come forward

On January 23rd, the city of Wuhan was sealed off, a measure I expected. In fact, my family had voluntarily quarantined themselves two days before the siege, and I explained to my wife's parents that I specifically asked them not to leave the house.

On 24 January, I received an e-mail from the French consulate informing us that the French government would arrange for the repatriation of French nationals to France to fill in their personal information as appropriate. I was extremely anxious, but said calmly to my wife, "I want you to go with Gaspard. I'll stay. I'm needed here. Think about it and let me know later. "

On the 24th, the second day of the Wuhan Blockade, medical resources were strained and French doctors at the International Hospital advised evacuations. There was no way to guarantee that the French could receive treatment here.

Our primary concern is the child, my child is just one year old, and the evacuation will ensure that my wife and child, should anything go wrong, can be treated.

Fred's in the studio

For me, I have been a Wuhan people, I did not want to leave, I can not leave. In case the family is in trouble, the store, staff, or even go to the hospital to help, even if it is only with the face of a foreigner to stand out to encourage everyone.

My wife was very ambivalent at the time. She knew that once I made a decision, it would be difficult to change it. On the one hand, if I took my son away and I was alone in Wuhan, she could not trust me at all. But if the whole family stayed behind, my one-year-old son was unfortunately infected, what are the chances of getting medical attention?

After much thought, she decided to stay with me. The days we've been in quarantine at home, we haven't had any symptoms, so we'll stay here as a family.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In front of the Consulate in Wuhan on Feb. 8, the three flags were China, France and the European Union

Why did we finally give up four evacuations?

The second French evacuation took place the day after the first, and we were informed that the aircraft would be able to take back the French and some of the rest of Europe. I wavered again and asked Vicky, "why don't we go this time? " But she saw on the news that the central government had sent someone to take over, and supplies from all over the country were beginning to support Wuhan, which she said was good news.

The third evacuation took place on 1 February, when a British arranged plane arrived and the French consulate organized the evacuation of more than 200 people from Wuhan, but we were determined to stay. I don't know why, but I have a strong feeling that we are safe at home.

Most recently, on February 21st, France again evacuated more than 60 French and other EU nationals back to Europe.

Some French expats have been placed in 14-day isolation in the southern town of Calitroué, a popular tourist resort in southern France

I heard that some of the French evacuees were quarantined at resort hotels in southern France, and some were quarantined at fire schools, monitored by specialized medical and security personnel, and could not leave until 14 days, fortunately, none of those who returned to France were infected.

Several of my foreign friends have also decided to stay. They are isolated from each other at home and, like other Chinese, exchange messages and cheer each other up on Wechat groups.

What is more tragic is that a French friend of mine is stranded abroad. His flight has been cancelled. He can not go back to Wuhan, nor is it convenient to go back to France. I'll contact him on Wechat and share with him the latest news of the epidemic.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Street view of Wuhan outside Fred's window

Self-segregation in Wuhan:

I learned to make hot and dry noodles

Our community did not arrange the distribution of supplies, since the quarantine, we only went out shopping three times. I ride my scooter to the nearest supermarket to pick up a week's worth of groceries.

I follow the French news and the Xinhua APP Every day. Now there is panic in France. The government has set up a special line to help people answer questions about the new type of pneumonia. Some people will ask, "Can I get infected if I eat Chinese food? " "Can I safely open a package received from China? " I thought it was funny, but in Wuhan, I felt at ease.

I'm a fashion designer, and I'm still working every day: Wearing a mask, gloves, riding a bike to the studio to do design, but all alone, no contact with others. (as of press time, Wuhan has been closed to the whole community management, the whole family no longer go out.)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Fred's hot and dry noodles

In addition to designing and managing the store, my wife works as a music teacher, taking care of Darling at home and doing household chores, and occasionally teaches online piano lessons. We usually have dinner and watch a movie together in the evening.

I also used this idle time, learned to do Wuhan's hot-and-dry noodles.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Working from home and with children became a regular part of Fred's isolation

In addition to the health of the family,

Most worried about the store's operation after the outbreak

After a month of isolation, my one-year-old son was the happiest. Before we went to work, the child was taken care of by my in-laws during the day and returned at night. Now he is so happy, I can have so much time to play with him, to read to him, coax him to sleep, father-son relationship has become better.

No one in our family is ill at present. We did not take any preventive medicine, is in accordance with the usual habit of vitamin supplements such as health products, adhere to the morning and evening temperature monitoring. Vicky's parents were separated in another neighborhood, and she was in perfect health, which was the best thing that could have happened.

What worries me most is my family in France. I report to my mother on Wechat every day, what I have for dinner, my body temperature in the morning and at night, etc. . My mother had been to Wuhan before. She saw on the news that the street she had walked on was now empty and sad. She prayed for Wuhan and me every day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A corner of Fred's studio

This outbreak has also had a great impact on our stores, I am now more worried about business, three stores closed for more than a month of losses is still very large.

We're not alone. All the stores are closed. We don't know when we'll be able to open again. This is the most concerned problem of all Wuhan shopkeepers. But I will be patient waiting for the government to resume business notice, before that, I have to do is to ensure the safety and health of family members.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hand-drawn drawings during the outbreak

As Xiaoyu puts it, "assertive warmth" may be the best decision a family can make in a crisis.

May the epidemic end, each separated family, together as soon as possible.
